{{Infobox flag | Name = Flag of the Hispanicity | Article = Flag of the Hispanicity | Nickname = ''Bandera de la Hispanidad'' | Morenicks = | Image_size = 300px | Image = Flag of the race.svg | Use = | Symbol = | Proportion = 1:2 | Adoption = 12 October 1932 | Design = | Type = International | Designer = Ángel Camblor }}
The '''Flag of the Hispanicity''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]: ''Bandera de la Hispanidad''){{efn-lr|Formerly known as "Flag of the Hispanic race" (Spanish: ''Bandera de la raza hispánica'')}} is a [[flag]] sometimes used to represent the [[Hispanic]] people or [[Hispanidad|Hispanic community]].<ref>Raeside, Rob (ed.) (2008). [http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/int-raza.html "Flag of the Race"]</ref>
==Symbolism== {{Unsourced section|date=September 2017}} The Flag of the Hispanicity displays a white background with three purple crosses and a rising sun.
*The white [[Flag terminology#Description of standard flag parts and terms|field]] or background symbolizes peace and purity. *The [[Gold (color)|golden]] [[Inti]] [[Solar symbol|sun]] symbolizes the awakening of the new lands. *The three [[cross pattée|crosses pattée]] symbolize [[Christopher Columbus]]'s three ships, the ''[[Niña]]'', the ''[[Pinta (ship)|Pinta]]'', and the ''[[Santa María (ship)|Santa María]]''. *The [[Purpure]] color of the [[cross]]es represents the [[Spanish language]] and comes from the ancient use of this color in the lion of the [[Kingdom of León]]'s flag, which was later incorporated with the [[Crown of Castile]].
==History== The flag was designed by Ángel Camblor, a [[Captain (land and air)|captain]] of the [[Uruguayan Army]]. He was the winner of a contest organized by [[Juana de Ibarbourou]] in 1932. The flag was first raised in [[Montevideo]], at the Independence Square, on October 12, 1932.
==Alternative use as the Flag of the Americas== The flag is also sometimes occasionally alternately used to represent the entire geographical area of [[The Americas]] and not just as an [[ethnic flag]] of the [[Hispanic America]]n people.<ref>''Compton's Encyclopedia'', 1958 edition. See Volume F, section "Flags of the World"</ref><ref>Raeside, Rob (ed.) (2008). [http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/int-raza.html "Flag of the Americas"] (See final paragraph at the end of the web page.)</ref> The flag was officially adopted as the ''Flag of the Americas''—in this usage representing besides Hispanic Americans also [[Anglo-America|Anglo-Americans]], [[French colonization of the Americas|Franco-Americans]] (the [[French-speaking Quebecer|Québécois]], [[Haiti]]ans, [[Guadeloupe|Guadeloupians]], [[Martinique|Martininqians]], and [[French Guiana|French Guianians]]), [[Portuguese colonization of the Americas|Luso-Americans]], [[Dutch colonization of the Americas|Dutch Americans]] (the inhabitants of the [[Dutch Antilles]] and [[Suriname]]), and [[Greenlanders]]—by all member countries of the [[Pan-American Conference]] at their Seventh Assembly in 1933.
==See also== * [[Flags of the World]] * [[Flags of Europe]] * [[La Raza]]
