{{unreferenced|date=February 2015}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = Paul Cézanne 169.jpg | caption = | painting_alignment = | image_size = 300px | title = Rideau, Cruchon et Compotier | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[Paul Cézanne]] | year = 1893-1894 | medium = oil on canvas | material = | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = 23.5 | width_imperial = 28.75 | length_imperial = | diameter_metric = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave this parameter blank—either don't include it, or include the default cm. Not including it will default it to cm.--> | imperial_unit = in<!--don't leave this parameter blank—either don't include it, or include the default in. Not including it will default it to in.--> | city = | museum = | coordinates = <!-- Only use for the exact coordinates of the artwork itself (and only where known) and not for the coordinates of the museum. Leave blank if coordinates are not known. --> | owner = }} '''''Rideau, Cruchon et Compotier''''' is a [[painting]] created circa 1893 to 1894 by [[France|French]] [[artist]] [[Paul Cézanne]] (19 January 1839 – 22 October 1906). It is considered [[List of most expensive paintings|the most expensive]] [[still life]] ever sold at an auction.
Cézanne was famous for painting still lifes which expressed complex emotions while still being based upon carefully observed reality. Paintings of this type would eventually lead to the creation of new art styles during the 20th century such as [[Cubism]].
==Ownership history==
The painting went through the possession of [[Paris]] dealer [[Ambroise Vollard]], [[Cornelis Hoogendijk]], [[Paul Rosenberg (art dealer)|Paul Rosenberg]], [[Albert C. Barnes]], and the [[Carroll Carstairs]] Gallery. This painting was sold at [[Sotheby's]], [[New York City]] on 10 May 1999 for $60,502,500 (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US-GDP|60.5025|1999|r=1}} million in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{Inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), a record price, during the sale of the [[Whitney family]] collection. The painting was later resold at a loss.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}
